Clarinda Volleyball Tournament on Saturday, Sept. 5th

Thank you for all your work and patients as we continue to work to keep activities going. Have a great day and good luck tonight!

post_text: This will be the last week for the summer lunch program located at Clarinda High School. We want to thank the countless number of volunteers both adults & students that have helped hand out lunches, deliver lunches, and sack up the lunches. Without the help and support from multiple entities in Clarinda, this would not have been possible. The lunch program has been going strong since mid-March when school was released due to COVID -19. Starting next week the kitchen staff will direct their focus to prepare for the start of the 2020-2021 school year. Stop by on Wednesday & Friday this week to pick up lunch and say one last thank you to our amazing volunteers.

post_text:
The School District will be implementing a new messaging system called SchoolMessenger. This will replace the message system the district is currently utilizing. You will still receive emails and voice calls but will need to opt-in to receive text messages. A text message campaign will start on June 1st, asking you to opt-in to receive text messages from the school. Reply “Y” to the text if you’d like to receive text message alerts. Your number will not be shared.

Please Sign-up for New Text Message Alert Notifications from CCSD.
Questions may be directed to technology@clarindacsd.org.

After June 1, you will still have the option to opt-in by texting "Y" to 67587 or by scanning the QR code on the flyer.

5:30 JV Softball & Baseball
7:30 Varsity Softball & Baseball

For the first time since March 12th, KMA Sports will have live broadcasts tonight with Clarinda/Shenandoah baseball on KMA 960 and softball on KMA-FM 99.1. T

Once again thank you! The support from the community is absolutely amazing!

Iowa Girls High School Athletic Union (IGHSAU)
April 17 at 12:50 PM ·

Following today’s Iowa PK-12 school closure update, all Iowa Girls High School Athletic Union (IGHSAU) and Iowa High School Athletic Association spring sports are officially canceled due to #COVID19.

📰 : https://ighsau.org/news/iowa-high-school-spring-sports-canceled/

We would like to thank our participants, coaches, administrators, officials, and fans for their passion, patience, and effort this spring. This is an especially unfortunate conclusion for the Class of 2020, and we’ll work to support them in the coming days. #iahsseniors

#IGHSAU #IowaGirl

post_text:
Good Evening Cardinal Families!

Last week, the State of Iowa presented options for continuous learning as we move forward while school districts are currently not in session. Clarinda School Administrators, instructional leaders and teachers have been working on that plan for our students. Building administrators have sent both an email and a text to families outlining what that continuous learning will look like for your child. Please make sure you check your email, text, SeeSaw or Schoology for that information. If you have any questions please contact your building administrator.

We miss you. Have a great evening!

Clarinda CSD
Good afternoon, Cardinal Families! We hope this message finds you all healthy and safe! Last week after the Governor determined that is was in the public health interest of the state for Iowa schools to remain closed until April 30, 2020, the Iowa Department of Education provided public school districts with guidance on continuous learning for students. Clarinda CSD has elected to provide Voluntary Educational Enrichment Opportunities K-12. These may include paper packets, teleconferencing, online instruction or other outreach activities. Student participation is voluntary, and no grading or credit will be given. The goal will be to engage with learners and provide feedback. Administrators and teachers will be working this week to gather materials and are developing a plan to get materials to you. Continuous learning activities will begin on Monday, April 13, 2020.

As special state task forces gather to determine the most recent information and guidance on learning, financial, sanitation, transportation, meal service, and other operational necessities within a school district, we are called to be flexible and adaptable. In some instances, legislation and code are waiving restrictions while in others, restrictions are being applied. As an administrative team, we are responding accordingly and sharing information with you as soon as possible. Attached you will find COVID-19 Guidance Provisions of Continuous Learning which was sent out by the Department of Education late this afternoon.

Our chalkboard project supports words of hope and love for our service providers. Beyond words, please consider other ways to join efforts to address the shortage of face masks with shields used for patient care. Attached, you will find two documents with guidance on how to make PPE for health care facilities.

Have a safe and wonderful weekend!

post_text:
Good afternoon, Cardinals! Our CCSD Feeding The Birds program, which provides meals to Clarinda community students and families has been a HUGE success! Our community and partners have stepped up to meet the needs during this challenging time. On Wednesday, 296 student bags and 93 adult bags were distributed to citizens of Clarinda. Each bag consists of 1 breakfast and 1 lunch. Adult meals run $2.85 each. Adult pricing is at product cost only, and by law, cannot be paid from school funds. As our orders grow (up to 40 today) we want to be able to continue to provide for nutritional needs of families during these challenging times. If you or someone you know is interested in supporting this successful program, please consider sending a monetary donation to:

Clarinda Community School District
Attn: Feeding The Birds
423 E. Nodaway St.
Clarinda, IA 51632
#ClarindaKind

Good Afternoon!

"Backpack Program"
In partnership with Clarinda Regional Health Center. We will be making sure the backpack program continues starting this week as well. We are hopeful for delivery no later than Wednesday!

"Meals"
Just like last week meals are available for pick-up at Clarinda High School from 11-1 on Monday, Wednesday, & Friday. You will get two lunches & two breakfasts as you drive through. When you pull up just let one of the volunteers know how many meals you need. Also, they will need to know how many of those meals are for kids and how many are for adults. We appreciate all your help as we work to make our process as smooth as possible.

"Updated Info"
Remember to continue to check out http://www.clarinda.k12.ia.us/ school page for updated school information. You can also check out information on home learning options provided by TLC Staff, Teacher, & Administration under the "Important information regarding school closing"

Have a great week and stay safe!

Current understanding is that COVID-19 spreads mostly from person to person through respiratory droplets produced when a person coughs or sneezes, similar to how flu spreads. Most person-to-person spread happens when people are in close contact. It is also possible that the virus can spread when someone touches a contaminated surface and then touches their mouth, nose, or eyes.

Dear CCSD family,

Please come if you are able!

What: Parent & Community Education (PACE) Event
Topic: Anxiety & Perfectionism: How to Help Your Student Cope
When/Where: Wednesday, January 22
7:00 a.m. and Noon - Garrison House
5:00 p.m. - CMS/Garfield Elementary Media Center (PTA mtg after at 6:30!)
(In the event of weather late start/early dismissal, PACE is canceled).

In February 2019, a Pew survey found that 70 percent of teens say anxiety and depression is a “major problem” among their peers, and an additional 26 percent say it’s a minor problem (NEA). Please come and discuss strategies that will help your students learn and thrive, despite worries, perfectionism, and anxiety. Everyone is welcome!

post_text:
Dear Community Members and Families,

As the week closes and we take time to rest, relax, reunite with family and friends, and reflect on the season, I invite you to consider baking cookies or holiday treats to celebrate our amazing teachers and staff! On Friday, December 20th, we are hosting professional learning at Clarinda High School. As a send-off to winter break, I'd like to have each teacher leave with a plate filled with at least one dozen cookies or treats. Yes, that is a lot of cookies; however, the time, energy, care, and expertise our staff extends in support of students equates to a lot of hours. If you plan to bring a large number of goodies, would you please email me. This will help in planning and will tell me how many hours I need to roll up my sleeves and bake.

Thank you for your support! The district appreciates your partnership. Feel free to pass the invitation along to anyone you feel might be interested in joining us!

Take care,

Chris

Chris Bergman
Superintendent
Clarinda Community School District

post_text:
The Lied Public Library and Clarinda Community Schools are excited to offer a professional book club to our community!

The Professional Bite-Sized Book Club is a book club for busy people that will meet every 2 weeks for 30 minutes to discuss a few chapters at a time.

We’ll read a few chapters every two weeks then meet for 30 minutes to discuss until we’ve read and discussed the complete book. You'll have your choice of discussion times that work best for you, as a group will meet in the morning and again over lunch. There’s even an option to attend online from your office or home. Each book will focus on various leadership skills and community development that will spark inspiration, discussion, and discovery.

See the attached flyer for more information and the title of the book!

Participants are encouraged to purchase their own copy of the book, however, the library does have multiple FREE eBook copies available via Bridges or Hoopla Digital.

For more information contact Andrew 712-542-2416 or andrew@clarindapubliclibrary.org

Clarinda Herald-Journal
October 10, 2019 at 2:03 PM ·

Friday is Clarinda's homecoming parade and pep rally. The parade starts at 2 p.m. and will go around the Clarinda square. The pep rally follows.

If it rains, the pep rally will be moved to the high school. (Can you do a parade inside the high school? We don't know.) As soon as we know if things get moved to the high school, we will let our followers know too.

Friday's weather is supposed to give us a sample of winter weather temperatures. Today's dress up day for homecoming is Minnesota. Too bad that wasn't planned for Friday. If you're not sure what Minnesota attire is like, maybe Cloe and Alex from the spring play last school year will help. (Wear your Cardinal colors Friday!)

Interim Superintendent Chris Bergman plans to meet the public beginning at 1:45 p.m. Friday in front of the Clarinda Chamber of Commerce office.

Monday, September 30th, is a late start. Clarinda CSD's Kid Academy will be in full action. Here are some important details -

* Students can come as early as 7:30 AM. Walk to or drop off on the middle school side.

* Buses will run 90 minutes late.

* Crosswalk monitors will be available on 15th & 16th Street at both 7:30 am & 9:10 am.

* Breakfast will be served from 7:30 am -9:00 am. The hot breakfast option will run from 7:30 am-8:15 am.

* Space for homework/tutoring and various interactive stations will be available.

Clarinda Brokaw FFA Chapter
September 24, 2019 at 4:38 PM ·

The Brokaw FFA Soils Judging team placed 2nd at the Southwest District Soils Judging contest held today at the Armstrong Research Farm! The team consisted of Shayla Harris, Jalyn Sharr, Carter Larson, Lanie Garrett, and alternate Kristen Smith. All four team members placed in the top 10 with Jalyn placing 9th, Carter placing 7th, Shayla placing 6th, and Lanie placing 5th. There were 27 total teams today with 105 students making up the district teams. The second place finish qualifies our team to compete at the state competition on October 12. Congratulations to these members!

post_text:
Excited for our students as we continue to grow our partnership with Clarinda Regional Health. This year all high school football players will be wearing the new impact helmets and all youth through middle school football players will have guardian caps. These decisions are easy when it is in the best interest of our kids and safety.

Along with that we would like to welcome Logan Wood to our Cardinal Family. Logan was hired as an athletic trainer at Clarinda Regional Health. He will be working side by side our coaches and administrators. Just in the short few weeks that he has been here we are very grateful for his presence and help at practices.

Looking forward to a great start to the new school year!

Clarinda Brokaw FFA Chapter

Brokaw FFA members have been busy at the Page County Fair this week. Activities include the Children’s Barnyard, conducting the livestock judging contest, helping with rope making and the pedal pull, and Bradlie Wilmes showing her heifer in the beef show. Thanks to all of the FFA members who have volunteered their time to help out along with the parents as well!
